ariety of folk practices and traces their development from the time of slavery through the Great Migrations. She explores how they have continued into the present and their relationship with alternative medicines. Through conversations with black Americans, she demonstrates how herbs, charms, and rituals continue folk healing performances. Mitchem shows that these practices are not simply about healing; they are linked to expressions of faith, delineating aspects of a holistic epistemology and pointing to disjunctures between African American views of wellness and illness and those of the culture of institutional medicine.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aAfrican AmericansvFolklore. 0aAfrican AmericansxMedicine. 7aRELIGION / Ethnic & Tribal.2bisacsh  aAfrican.  aAmerican.  aMitchem.  aabout.  aaspects.  abetween.  aculture.  adelineating.  adisjunctures.  aepistemology.  aexpressions.  afaith.  ahealing.  aholistic.  aillness.  ainstitutional.  alinked.  amedicine.  apointing.  apractices.  ashows.  asimply.  athat.  athese.  athey.  athose.  aviews.  awellness.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814759622423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814759622/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK